observations.recommendation:
Direct the GSO to cause the immediate marking of all the vehicles and strictly observe all the rules and regulations cited above on the official marking of the vehicles; 


Require all department heads to observe the rules and regulations on the use of government vehicles and prohibit its usage without official marking, agency seal and red plate; and 


Require the GSO to make a continuous follow up and secure the government plates for recently acquired vehicles to the supplier/seller to expedite the processing of the permanent red plates issued by the Land Transportation Office (LTO).

Require the Bids and Awards Committee to strictly comply with the provisions of RA 9184 in the conduct of public bidding and awarding of the contracts; 
Direct the BAC members, BAC Secretariat and TWG to internalize the different rules and regulations set forth by RA 9184;

Require the end-users to attach a copy of PPMP and APP of the projects contracted in order to guide management in the procurement of goods and infrastructure projects and furnish COA of the same for audit/evaluation purposes. Henceforth, no procurement shall be undertaken unless it is in accordance with the approved APP of the procuring entity; 

Direct the BAC to invite observers in writing in all the stages of the procurement process in accordance with the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and post all government procurement opportunities, results of bidding and related information in the PhilGEPS website; 

Instruct the BAC to submit the contract within the prescribed period; and 

BAC Secretariat to ensure that bidders submit complete eligibility requirements and all documentary requirements before signing the contract.

Direct the HRMO and Municipal Accountant to expedite the reconciliation of records with the GSIS to come up with the updated service records; 

Direct the HRMO/AAO to observe prompt submission of ARA to GSIS whenever there are changes in members’ data to ensure timely updating of the GSIS database and prevent inaccuracies in billing statements;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to identify employees affected by the unreconciled balances of the GSIS and Pag-Ibig and validate the amounts with official payroll records; and

Upon confirmation, the Municipal Treasurer should remit the unpaid contributions and loan amortizations immediately to prevent penalties and interest charges.

Constitute and require Department Heads of the LGU to cooperate/assist the inventory team in the conduct of physical inventory of properties found in their respective department to facilitate and hasten the preparation of inventory report. Likewise, the Inventory Committee should consolidate the reports submitted by the Department Heads and render a Report on the Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE);

The Inventory Committee (a) to coordinate with the Property Division or the General Supply Office, plan or strategize the conduct of complete physical inventory, and prepare a Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) taking into consideration the specific assignments/duties of the Committee members, the cut-off date and a schedule specifying the dates and locations of the inventory taking activities from start up to the targeted completion of the physical inventory, (b) to submit to the COA Audit Team the PIP at least ten (10) days before the scheduled start of inventory taking activities, (c) to conduct physical count of PPE by type and by department in accordance with the approved PIP at the end of each year and following the guidelines and procedures laid in COA Circular in COA Circular No. 2020-006 and (d) to submit RPCPPE using the prescribed format to the Municipal Accountant Office, the MGSO, and the Audit Team upon completion of the physical count;

The Municipal General Services Office (a) to update the property cards for each class of PPE, (b) to work together with the accounting office to reconcile the property cards with the property ledger cards, and (c) prepare Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) using the format prescribed should there have been found unserviceable, obsolete and/or no longer needed;

The Municipal Accountant (a) to maintain property ledger cards and (b) to take up the necessary accounting entries on the affected accounts; 

The coordination of the Municipal Accountant, MGSO, and the Inventory Committee to reconcile the physical inventory of the PPE with the ledger cards and the property cards; and

To undertake one time cleansing of PPE account balances as provided in COA Circular No. 2020-006 “to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability”.

Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory of the local roads under the jurisdiction of the municipality and render a Report on the Physical count of the Road Networks System;

Instruct the Designated General Service Officer to render a Report on Local Road Network, Road Map and to keep a complete Local Road Network Property Cards for all roads and its components; and

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to review the schedule of the Road Networks account and Registry of Public Infrastructure maintained in the previous years in order to reconcile and identify the roads under that lump sum amount of P29.6 million.

Strictly follow the perpetual inventory method in recording and accounting of inventories;

Require physical count of supplies and materials at least once a year in compliance with Section 194 of the GAM for LGU’s, Volume I and submit the required Report on Physical Count of Inventories (RCPI);

Conduct physical count of unused inventories, if any, for the recognition of inventories accounts reported without balances in the books. Submit Report of Physical Count of Inventories thereafter;

Verify the existence, correctness and propriety of expenses set up as Accounts Payable amounting to P4,804,014.40, otherwise derecognize in the books;

Prepare and maintain the required forms, subsidiary records and periodic reports in relation to receipt and issuance of inventories for distribution; and

Take up the necessary adjusting entries for the incorrect use of accounts and the transactions recorded in the CkDJ but not in the GL in the amount of ₱24,127.00. Use the appropriate accounts provided under Annex B of COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015.

Require the Supply Officer and RHU to coordinate and come up with a clear defined responsibility for proper inventory-taking, reporting, supervision and disposition of the transferred drugs, medicines, medical supplies from DOH, PHO and the Commission on Population and Development;

Require the Supply Officer to inform the Municipal Accountant and furnish her with the receipt of asset for her to recognize it in the books basing on the PTRs issued by the DOH;

Ensure that the receiving officer requires that PTRs are duly approved and value of items received are indicated properly otherwise coordinate with the DOH and PHO source agency for that matter; and

Require preparation of Distribution and Utilization Report for accounting, evaluation and documentation purposes.

Require the Municipal Accountant to review, analyze and validate the payables and prepare the necessary adjusting entry/ies to exclude payables without valid claims or supporting documents to validate their legality, and on dormant accounts, when established;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare properly and correctly the schedule and maintain subsidiary ledgers that will support Accounts Payable;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Budget Officer to devise a schedule and cut off period of recording obligations of the Municipality at year end and to ensure that all officials and employees specially Department Heads are informed in advance of the schedule to avoid issues on time constraint; and

Recognize liability only for claims that are supported by proper and sufficient evidence which will support the validity and legality of the claims in accordance with Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445 and Section 46 of PD No. 1177.

Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer to prepare and maintain his Report of Collections and Deposits and make deposits in the bank using his RCD’s and to deposit collections intact and daily or at the frequency prescribed by the regulation;

Require the Collectors to remit collections on a daily basis; and

Give priority to the Acting Municipal Treasurer’s use of the vehicle in order to comply with the regulation.

Direct the Municipal Accountant to maintain special account in the general fund for the 20% Development Fund and supported by a separate set of subsidiary ledgers for each development project charged to the said fund, whether current or continuing, and prepare financial statements exclusive for the 20% DF;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to make a representation with the bank to utilize the bank account solely for transfers of NTA share, and open and maintain separate bank account exclusive for the 20% Development Fund; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasure and Municipal Budget Officer to determine the exact amount of the LDF remaining in the general fund proper which will be transferred to the new LDF’s bank account.

Require the MPDC to conduct a thorough planning for the implementation of development projects by clearly identifying the project procurement timelines as laid down in the PPMP and APP or their equivalent;

Require the MPDC, Municipal Budget Office and Municipal Accountant to review and assess the unimplemented projects /unobligated fund especially those from prior years and consider the possibility of proposing and re-appropriation to other priority development projects;

Instruct the Municipal Engineer and Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator to conduct regular monitoring and evaluation of the projects and at the same time respond to the causes of delays on the actual implementation and prepare the Procurement Monitoring Report; and

Require the Municipal Engineer to fast track the preparation of the Program of Works for the projects not yet implemented or started and to prepare and submit monthly monitoring report on the status of awarded projects.

Create inventory committee; to prepare a timetable for the conduct of Physical Inventory including Local Road Network and coordinate with the Inventory Committee members for a cohesive planning;

Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant of the complete description and cost segregation of the road networks to facilitate the preparation of the subsidiary ledgers for roads and its components;

Require the General Services Officer to prepare and maintain the Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components including a Road Map and to prepare a Report on Local Road Network at the end of accounting period;

Require the General Supply Officer to initiate the disposal in accordance with the requirements provided in COA Circular No. 92-386 dated October 20, 1992 and Section 79 of PD No. 1445;

Require the Municipal Accountant to disclose in their notes under Property, Plant and Equipment, the estimated amount of all the unserviceable motor vehicles subject for disposition; and

 Require the Municipal Accountant and General Supply Officer to maintain complete property ledger cards and property cards respectively for all PPE owned by the agency.

