Enroll the Municipal bank accounts in the lbpiaccess website to download the bank statements to ensure timely preparation and submission of the bank reconciliation statement.

The Local Chief Executive to create inventory committee; to prepare a timetable for the conduct of Physical Inventory including Local Road Network and coordinate with the Inventory Committee members for a cohesive planning;
The General Supply Officer to initiate the disposal in accordance with the requirements provided in COA Circular No. 92-386 dated October 20, 1992 and Section 79 of PD No. 1445;
The Municipal Accountant to disclose in their notes under Property, Plant and Equipment, the estimated amount of all the unserviceable motor vehicles subject for disposition; and
The Municipal Accountant and General Supply Officer to maintain complete property ledger cards and property cards respectively for all PPE owned by the agency.

We have recommended and management agreed to:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to submit the required interim financial statements and quarter reports on unliquidated cash advances and transfer of funds;
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to submit quarterly a Status of Appropriations, Allotments, and Obligations (SAOB);
Direct the Municipal Engineering Office to ensure that quarter reports on projects are timely submitted. Also, it is directed that the Supervising Auditor (SA) thru the Audit Team Leader (ATL) is informed within ten (10) days after the award of the contract or before the start of the program/activity that the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices are already posted.
The OIC-Municipal Budget Officer committed to submit the SAOB as prescribed in Section 70 of the LGU NGAS Manual. Likewise, the Local Chief Executive has already issued a Memorandum dated February 18, 2019 directing the OIC-MPDC and Municipal Engineer to ensure that a written communication will be given to the Audit Team Leader within  ten (10) days after the award of the contract or before the start of any project.

We have recommended and management agreed to:
Direct the MDRRMO to fast track the implementation of projects by close coordination with the GSO, devise a monitoring tool of all projects, and to review the PPA’s especially those from previous years to determine its responsiveness to the needs of the Municipality or to meet the purpose of the fund;
Advise the Local Chief Executive to augment manpower under the MDRRMO;
Require the Municipal Accountant prepare the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF using the prescribed format in COA Circular 2012-002 and require the LDRRMO to submit such report on or before the 15th day after the end of each month to the COA Auditor.
The Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer is now doing a review of the financial plans and ensures that audit recommendations will be implemented the soonest.

We recommended to –

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prioritize the identification of those termed as unverified and unrecorded reconciling items in the bank reconciliation statements;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to support the bank reconciliation statements with subsidiary ledger of the specific bank account.

We recommended and management agreed to direct the Cashier/Accountable Officer – 

To maintain a cashbook for each type of cash advances and each type of fund;

To record daily his collections in the cashbook in ink and in the order they occur;

To balance, rule and close at the end of the day his cashbook and foot and close the books at the end of each month; and

To reconcile her cashbook with the accounting records regularly or at least once in every quarter to establish the correct balance of accountability of the AO at the earliest time possible. Any account found unrecorded can be easily traced and the necessary corrections/recording can be effected immediately.

We recommended to the Municipal Accountant the following:

Implement the “No Liquidation, No Cash Advance” policy.  Discontinue the practice of granting new cash advances to disbursing officer and/or officials and employees while there are still unliquidated cash advances;
Inform the employees concerned to return or refund immediately to the collecting officer any cash advance which was no longer needed or had not been used for a period of two (2) months;
Ensure the settlement of cash advances prior to the retirement or separation of officials or employees from service; 
Monitor closely the immediate liquidation of all cash advances;
Deduct on a staggered basis an appropriate and reasonable amount from the monthly salary of concerned officers and employees the unliquidated cash advances; and
Comply strictly with Section 89 of Presidential Decree 1445, otherwise, send demand letters to the concerned employees before filing of malversation charge of concerned accountable officer shall be enforced.

We recommended the management to require the Office of the Municipal Accountant and the Office of the Municipal Treasurer to observe the following:

Submit the Report of Checks Issued (RCI) with checks presented chronologically and to include the cancelled/voided checks;
Supply all the required data in the Liquidation Report (LR);
Submit the Consolidated Reports of Accountability for Accountable Forms (CRAAF) monthly to COA; and
Maintain Subsidiary Ledgers (SLs) by year for the Development Fund, Disaster Risk Reduction Management Fund and the collections, remittances of the collectors to facilitate verification and monitoring of the said accounts’ balances and other Subsidiary Ledgers.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following actions:

Preparation, submission and implementation of a plan for the safe and sanitary management of solid waste;
Review and update every year of the plan by the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board as required by law to ensure its sustainability, relevance and effectiveness;
Collaboration of campaigns with the barangay officials concerned;
Strict implementation shall be continued on waste segregation, and thorough collection of waste based on set schedules; and
Conversion of the open dumpsite into a controlled dumpsite.

Recommendations:

The Local Chief Executive should see to it that all of the 20% development projects be implemented for the realization of its socio-economic and environmental development programs;
The Municipal Engineer should conduct regular monitoring and evaluation of the projects and at the same time responding to the causes of delays on the actual implementation. Likewise, she should make a report addressed to the Local Chief Executive;
The Local Chief Executive should compel all implementing units to submit monthly or quarterly to the Municipal Planning Development Office (MPDO) the status of implementation of projects assigned to them as indicated in the Annual Investment Plan; and 
Finally, the Local Chief Executive should take immediate action in order that the constituents may immediately benefit on the said development projects.

